HEADWORD: Impressment
<hw>Im*press"ment</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧m*pr⟦ecr⟧s"m⟦eit⟧nt)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of seizing for public use, or of impressing
into public service; compulsion to serve; <as>as, the
<ex>impressment</ex> of provisions or of sailors</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The great scandal of our naval service -- <qex>impressment</qex>
-- died a protracted death.</q> <rj><qau>J. H. Burton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Impressor</ent>⟦br⟧
